goals.question: What is the relationship between income and health?
goals.visualization: scatter plot of income vs health
goals.rationale: This visualization can help us understand if there is a correlation between income and health. We can see if countries with higher income also have better health outcomes.

goals.question: What is the distribution of income across regions?
goals.visualization: box plot of income by region
goals.rationale: This visualization can help us understand if there are any significant differences in income across different regions. We can see if there are any outliers or if the income distribution is skewed in any way.

goals.question: What is the most common region in the dataset?
goals.rationale: This visualization can help us understand the distribution of countries across different regions. We can see which region has the most countries in the dataset.

goals.question: What is the relationship between population and income?
goals.visualization: scatter plot of population vs income
goals.rationale: This visualization can help us understand if there is a correlation between population and income. We can see if countries with larger populations also have higher incomes.

goals.question: What is the distribution of health across regions?
goals.visualization: box plot of health by region
goals.rationale: This visualization can help us understand if there are any significant differences in health outcomes across different regions. We can see if there are any outliers or if the health distribution is skewed in any way.

import matplotlib.pyplot as plt
import matplotlib.ticker as ticker
import pandas as pd

def plot(data: pd.DataFrame):
    plt.figure(figsize=(6, 6))
    plt.scatter(data['income'], data['health'])
    plt.xlabel('Income')
    plt.ylabel('Health')
    
    if len(plt.xticks()[0]) > 20:
        plt.gca().xaxis.set_major_locator(ticker.MaxNLocator(20))
    
    plt.title('What is the relationship between income and health?', wrap=True)
    return plt;

chart = plot(data)
chart.show()

import matplotlib.pyplot as plt
import matplotlib.ticker as ticker
import pandas as pd

def plot(data: pd.DataFrame):
    plt.figure(figsize=(6, 6))
    box_plot = data.boxplot(column='income', by='region', grid=False)
    plt.xticks(rotation=45)
    if len(plt.xticks()[0]) > 20:
        box_plot.xaxis.set_major_locator(ticker.MaxNLocator(20))
    plt.title("What is the distribution of income across regions?")
    plt.suptitle("")
    plt.xlabel("Region")
    plt.ylabel("Income")
    return plt;

chart = plot(data)
chart.show()

import matplotlib.pyplot as plt
import matplotlib.ticker as ticker
import pandas as pd

def plot(data: pd.DataFrame):
    plt.figure(figsize=(6, 6))
    region_counts = data['region'].value_counts()
    region_counts.plot(kind='bar')
    plt.xlabel('Region')
    plt.ylabel('Count')
    plt.title('What is the most common region in the dataset?')
    if len(plt.xticks()[0]) > 20:
        plt.gca().xaxis.set_major_locator(ticker.MaxNLocator(20))
    plt.xticks(rotation=45)
    return plt;

chart = plot(data)
chart.show()
